Today was incredible!!!

I bounced around between mottchildren and umichmedicine for appointments today in preparation for my bone-anchored hearing aid (BAHA) placement surgery in a couple of months. I had a CT scan, an updated hearing test and the BAHA evaluation where I had the opportunity to try the device.

My hearing has gotten a little worse since last time which is a bummer, but it makes me even more grateful for assistive hearing technology. If youâ€™re new here, my hearing loss is actually not technically related to having Osteogenesis Imperfecta. There is OI-related hearing loss, but itâ€™s not what I have. Iâ€™ve done several IG posts & YT videos about it, if you want to learn more. ğŸ¤—

In this photo Im wearing a band that the device connects to with a magnet. I could just have the device on a band like this so that I wouldnâ€™t need another surgery, but the band is really tight and uncomfortable (IMO), + the fashion gal in me would not like to wear it all the time. Plus Iâ€™d get makeup all over it ğŸ˜œ I clearly have my priorities straight, right?! ğŸ˜‚

And this way, the surgically implanted BAHA, wonâ€™t need to be adjusted all the time because of the band. Itâ€™s just all around the best option *for me* to get it surgically implanted. There are many different types of BAHAs for different circumstances. My surgeon & I decided the best option would be the medel_global BoneBridge. I will actually be the first person at umichmedicine to have this specific one implanted which is so exciting ğŸ¤©

Being able to hear is such a gift, & I never realized how much Iâ€™ve missed over the years. I cannot wait to experience a whole new world in a few months! ğŸ˜

Our docs gave us the â€˜sealâ€™ of approval on this one. ğŸ˜‚
